<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMENTARY; GIANTS' YOUNG, REEVES WERE RIGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE LUPICA, NEWSDAY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The New York Giants already have won everything they need to win, whether they 
make the playoffs or not. They finish the NFL season with a quarterback in Dave 
Brown, and they finish with a chance at the playoffs. George Young and Dan 
Reeves gambled the whole season when they released Phil Simms, and won. 
</P>
<P>
 Simms deserved one more year from the Giants, and deserved to leave on his own 
terms. When he says they already would be in the playoffs if he were the 
quarterback, he is right. Maybe they would even be 10-5 instead of 8-7, and 
fighting with the Dallas Cowboys for first place, instead of fighting the rest 
of the world for the last wild-card berth. 
</P>
<P>
 The Giants come up winners anyway. If they finish with six consecutive 
victories after seven consecutive losses, if they somehow get to 9-7, this will 
go down as one of the crazy seasons in their history. Even at 8-8, it would be 
remembered that way. But after everything that happened to them, after all the 
interceptions and bad calls and losses, a .500 record is enough. Young and 
Reeves wanted to start the future right now. They have. They let the rest of us 
worry about Simms, and the past, and rode the thing out. 
</P>
<P>
 This does not mean Young is in the process of building one more Super Bowl 
team before he retires. It does not mean Young and Reeves get along much better 
than Young and Bill Parcells did. Maybe the only thing that would make this a 
really successful season for Reeves is if Young retired at the end of it and 
Reeves ended up with the whole operation. It does not change that Young and 
Reeves bet on Brown and won. 
</P>
<P>
 There were times during the losing streak when Reeves seemed to be losing his 
team, and his grip. There were questions about whether Young could still do the 
job. Here they both are, one game to go, right where they wanted to be when the 
season started. The whole thing did not fall apart on them and the Giants are 
alive. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Most nights I miss regular-season hockey about the way Roseanne seems to miss 
Tom. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 When Boomer Esiason was brought to New York, he was supposed to make the Jets 
better. Now it is the Jets who are supposed to make Boomer better. I'm glad 
Pete Carroll cleared that up for me this week. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The television announcers for the Knicks got so giddy after John Starks had 
one decent game I thought they were going to give him a big hug every time he 
hit the rim. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Steve Young will end up being a runaway choice as pro football's most valuable 
player. The way Young has played since the first month of the season, people 
will want to vote for him twice. 
</P>
<P>
 But I don't see how anyone can run away from Barry Sanders, one of the best 
players in NFL history having one of the best seasons we will ever be 
privileged enough to see. 
</P>
<P>
 Sanders with the ball in his hands has been the single most electrifying event 
of the NFL season. But the 49ers have the top record in the league, and might 
win another Super Bowl, and Young is going to be MVP. 
</P>
<P>
 Still, there ought to be an award for Sanders, who could rush for 2,000 yards, 
and who has lit up the sport as much as Young. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The Knicks scored 85 points Friday night. Shaquille O'Neal and Anfernee 
Hardaway scored 78. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Don Nelson gave Chris Webber a one-year out in his contract. Don Nelson traded 
Chris Webber. Now everything that is happening to Nelson and the Warriors is 
supposed to be Chris Webber's fault. 
</P>
</TEXT>
