<HEADLINE>
<P>
WOMAN'S LIFE WAS ON UPWARD CURVE WHEN CRASH SUDDENLY ENDED IT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KEN ELLINGWOOD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Donna Davis was remembered Monday as a well-liked school employee with a 
contagious laugh, whose life had taken a Cinderella turn and who was making 
plans for marriage. 
</P>
<P>
 Michael Rooney is a 29-year-old high school dropout and unemployed mechanic 
who had been sleeping at friends' homes or in his car, his mother said. 
</P>
<P>
 On Saturday evening, Davis, 34, of Brea was killed instantly and her boyfriend 
was severely injured when Rooney's car, going about 70 m.p.h., rear-ended 
theirs, police said. 
</P>
<P>
 Police were awaiting results of blood-alcohol tests before seeking criminal 
charges against Rooney. He was in stable condition with internal injuries 
Monday in a jail ward at Western Medical Center-Santa Ana, being held on 
suspicion of vehicular manslaughter and felony driving under the influence. 
</P>
<P>
 Results of blood tests were expected as early as today, said Huntington Beach 
Officer Michael H. Corcoran. 
</P>
<P>
 Davis' boyfriend, Mark McLaughlin, 41, of Garden Grove, was in critical 
condition at Western Medical Center-Santa Ana, Corcoran said.  
</P>
<P>
 Witnesses told police Rooney had been speeding on Adams Avenue when he crashed 
into Davis and McLaughlin near Magnolia Street in Huntington Beach just before 
7 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Davis, who is survived by children aged 7 and 9, was remembered Monday as a 
devoted mother and colleague whose ready laugh brightened the Fullerton School 
District business office where she had worked as a clerk for 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
 "She was a wonderful employee. It was one of the saddest scenes I've ever seen 
at work today," said district Supt. Duncan Johnson. "She brought real cheer 
into the workplace with her." 
</P>
<P>
 Davis had told friends of her hopes to marry in the next year or two, said her 
sister, Judy Fry. 
</P>
<P>
 "They were making a life together. She'd had a rough life up to this point and 
things were really looking up," Fry said. "It was one of those Cinderella 
things." 
</P>
<P>
 Rooney had been homeless and out of work for months, although he had a talent 
for fixing things, said his mother, Joy Rooney. She said Rooney stayed with his 
parents or friends or slept in the Chevrolet Blazer he was driving Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
