<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: A REAL-LIFE GRINCH 
STEALS GIFTS FOR DISABLED CHILDREN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ABIGAIL GOLDMAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A real-life Grinch slithered into a North Hollywood nonprofit organization and 
stole more than 100 presents intended for children with severe mental and 
emotional disabilities, officials said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 Many of the children are wards of the court and were not likely to receive any 
other Christmas gifts. 
</P>
<P>
 Staff members of the Dubnoff Center for Child Development and Educational 
Therapy arrived at the center's administrative offices Monday morning to find 
the presents, computer equipment, office furniture and a refrigerator gone. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials at the center estimate that the total losses, including the 
presents, was $20,000. Police said the theft occurred sometime during the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
 "These children have so very little to begin with," said Gil Freitag. "The 
amount of effort and goodwill and expectations that went into the preparation 
of these gifts was enormous, and to have them snatched from under us overnight 
has just been devastating." 
</P>
<P>
 The private agency has worked with children from throughout Los Angeles County 
for 46 years, Freitag said. More than 130 students attend the center's school 
and preschool programs and about 30 live in group homes. 
</P>
<P>
 The live-in children -- who range in age from 12 to 18 -- were asked to make 
lists of things they wanted for Christmas, Freitag said. Some of those items 
were donated and others were bought with donated money and wrapped by staff 
members. 
</P>
<P>
 Each child was to receive five presents, including such items as athletic 
shoes, cassette recorders, computer games, walkie-talkies, baseball cards and 
art supplies. Freitag said the gifts were to be a surprise, placed under 
Christmas trees in the group homes on Monday. He added that he will not tell 
the children what happened. 
</P>
<P>
 "They've experienced abandonment in major ways that have destroyed their hope 
that they could ever have a normal, happy, Christmas," Freitag said. "This 
would just confirm their worst fears." 
</P>
</TEXT>
