<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY ROUNDUP: GRIFFIN INDUSTRIES GETS LOAN FOR AFFORDABLE HOMES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Jack Searles 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Griffin Industries has received a $700,000 loan from Simi Valley's federal 
earthquake aid funds to build affordable housing in Simi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 Griffin was founded in 1993 by Paul E. Griffin III, a fifth-generation member 
of a home-building family. 
</P>
<P>
 The company said it will downsize the density now approved by the city's 
General Plan for a 45-acre site from 640 units to 416 units. The project in 
western Simi Valley will consist of single-family homes priced from $120,000 to 
$160,000. Construction will start in September, with units due to go on the 
market by spring, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
 Richard E. Niec, a Griffin senior vice president, praised city officials for 
helping the firm launch the project. Griffin has also received $3.7 million in 
financing from Great Western Bank for the project. 
</P>
<P>
 Simi Valley officials contacted the Department of Housing and Urban 
Development several months ago seeking permission to use some of the city's 
$5.5 million in earthquake assistance money to help Griffin purchase land for 
an affordable housing project. HUD approved the request in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
